issue.title: `additionalProperties` schema is not parsed correctly

labels.name: priority:p2
labels.description: Medium. Generally has a work-around and a smaller sub-set of customers is affected. SLA <=30 days

milestone.title: Backlog
milestone.description: Issues that have been committed to be worked on but have not yet been assigned to a backlog.

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
When parsing an OpenAPI spec which contains a schema for the `additionalProperties` field, the schema does not end up in the parsed `OpenApiDocument`. 

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the current behavior:

consider the following minimal spec (`example.yml`): 
```yaml
openapi: 3.0.0
info:
  title: Sample API
  version: 0.1.9
paths:
  /users:
    get:
      responses:
        "200":
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                type: object
                additionalProperties:
                  schema:
                    type: object
                    properties:
                      data:
                        type: string
```
And the code: 
```cs
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Models;
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Readers;

var document = new OpenApiStreamReader().Read(File.OpenRead("example.yml"), out var diagnostics);

var additionalProperties = document.Paths["/users"].Operations[OperationType.Get].Responses[
    "200"
].Content["application/json"]
    .Schema
    .AdditionalProperties;

Console.WriteLine(value: additionalProperties.Properties.Count); // prints "0"
```

This makes it impossible, to generate code based on the type of the additional properties (cf. [#microsoft/kiota/62](https://github.com/microsoft/kiota/issues/62) )

**Expected behavior**

I would expect the `additionalProperties` schema to be parsed and contain the schema of type `"object"` with the properties dictionary containing a field `data` of type `string`. 
 
**Additional context**

I think the parsing is in principle implemented in [OpenApiSchemaDeserializer.cs#L161](https://github.com/microsoft/OpenAPI.NET/blob/976c9f59adb53b846a935bb2c318d2364be1c333/src/Microsoft.OpenApi.Readers/V3/OpenApiSchemaDeserializer.cs#L161). However, somewhere there must be a bug.

comment.body:
@fpoppinga the `additionalProperties` field is already defined as an `OpenApiSchema` object so it shouldn't have a `schema` field nested within it. Instead the schema should be defined directly within the `additionalProperties` field. Try using this instead and you'll see the object being populated:
```yaml
openapi: 3.0.0
info:
  title: Sample API
  version: 0.1.9
paths:
  /users:
    get:
      responses:
        "200":
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                type: object
                additionalProperties:
                    type: object
                    properties:
                      data:
                        type: string
```

pull_request.title: Serializer Refactoring
pull_request.body:
Serializer Refactoring to support DI, reduce Code Duplication and simplify Future Updates of OpenAPI Version.
Unfortunately I do not know whether it is possible to use DI in Framework 4.6. thats why the Public API Test is failing.
Let me know if you agree with general concept and i would add Xml Comments and mark IOpenApiSerializable as Obsolete.
I could also write for Framework 4.6. an Explicit Serializer without DI.
